            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301209-268-person2248">
                  SARAH 
                  ATKINS
               <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2248" type="surname" value="ATKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2248" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2248" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Samuel Atkins - we live in <placeName id="t18301209-268-crimeloc1502">New Gravel-lane, Shadwell</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18301209-268-crimeloc1502" type="placeName" value="New Gravel-lane, Shadwell"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18301209-268-crimeloc1502" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301209-268-off1500 t18301209-268-crimeloc1502"></join>. The prisoner lodged in our house previous to the 1st of December, and left it that day - while he was there I missed a shirt and a waistcoat on the 30th of November; Mrs. Hunter produced some duplicates to me, in the prisoner's presence - in con<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183012090129"></xptr>sequence of what I heard I spoke to the prisoner, and went and got the things out of pawn with the duplicates; among the rest was this shirt at Mr. Purser's, and this waistcoat at Mr. Lance's - Mr. Lance did not appear against the prisoner.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. Did not you promise that if I would go with you to Mr. Hunter, you would say no more about it. A. No - I said it would be better for him to own to it, and he owned to all the duplicates.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301209-268-person2249">
                  FRANCIS 
                  HUNTER
               <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2249" type="surname" value="HUNTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2249" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2249" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at the sign of the Wheatsheaf in Wapping. The prisoner brought some duplicates to my bar, and told me to take care of them for him till he came from sea; I put them into my bar-drawer - I gave the same duplicates to my wife, and told her to give them to the prisoner or to Mrs. Atkins.</p>

               <p>SARAH ATKINS. Mr. Hunter said, in the prisoner's presence, that he had given her the duplicates to take care of - he did not say any thing to that.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301209-268-person2250">
                  CAROLINE 
                  PURSER
               <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2250" type="surname" value="PURSER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2250" type="given" value="CAROLINE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2250" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of 
               <persName id="t18301209-268-person2251">
                  Robert 
                  Purser
               <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2251" type="surname" value="Purser"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2251" type="given" value="Robert"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-person2251" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             -- he lives at Limehouse-causeway. Mrs. Atkins took a shirt out of pawn at our house; I have the counterpart of the duplicate - they exactly correspond; it was pawned by a seafaring person, on the 12th of November, but I have no recollection of the person.</p>
               <p>SARAH ATKINS. I am not sure whether the shirt had been up stairs or down, but it was in my house. and in my possession; I think it was where the prisoner could have access to it - the duplicate produced to me by Mr Hunter enabled me to get the waistcoat out of pawn; the prisoner went with me.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. When I left Mr. Atkins' house, he said he was very sorry, and he would not say any thing about the business, provided I conducted myself better - I went to his house on the Wednesday following, to see how much I owed him, and if I could raise the money to pay him - he never offered to take me then; I went on the Saturday night, and he said there was a letter at his house for me, and if I would go all should be right - when I went the letter had no money in it, as I expected, and he gave charge of me.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18301209-268-verdict1503" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18301209-268-verdict1503" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 24. - <rs id="t18301209-268-punish1504" type="punishmentDescription">
